If you have previously registered on tdtnews.com, and have a current online subscription you may login with your email and password. Online subscribers get access to all of the Temple Daily Telegram's online content, plus a digital replica of the print edition. Some third party content, including circulars may not be available online.

If you have questions regarding access, please contact circulation at tdtcir@tdtnews.com or 254-778-4444 between 8 a.m. and 5 p.m. Monday through Friday.

og.description: BELTON — There is no “I” in team or Olajuwon Taylor, and the Belton senior slot receiver/running back emphasizes that fact. He is a man that’s all about T-E-A-M. If he does his job, it will benefit the Tigers and be part of the group accomplishment — enough said.“I’m just one player,” the 5-foot-11, 185-pound Taylor said. “There are 10 other players on the field. If it was just me, we wouldn’t accomplish anything. The guys around me make me better.“The team is what it’s about and that includes the JV players that act as our scout team and make us better. The reserves, coaches — everybody has a role. These guys show up every day and work hard. They give their best on every play.”Taylor, who carried 33 times for 124 yards and caught four passes for 38 yards as a junior, will be a key offensive cog for Belton when it opens the season at 7 tonight against Waco University at Waco ISD Stadium.
og.title: Taylor relishes role with Tigers
